Part I - (Prosper Loan Exploration)¶

by (Kosiso Aniebue)¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

In [16]:
# Convert IncomeRange to ordinal categorical 
ordinal_var_dict = {'IncomeRange':['$0','$1-24,999','$25,000-49,999','$50,000-74,999','$75,000-99,999','$100,000+']}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    loans[var] = loans[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 113937 rows and 22 columns. Most of the columns are numeric but we also have categorical variables(both ordinal and nominal) and datetime variables.

However, I will be working with just 84853 rows and 11 of those columns

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

How does the length of the loan (Term) affect the Estimated Return?

What time of the year are people more likely to borrow?

Does being a homeowner affect the loan amount?

Does having a verifiable income ensure larger loan amounts?

How does the length of the loan (Term) affect the Borrowers Annual Percentage Rate (APR)?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

In order to explore all the hypotheses put forth, I believe the features Term, Estimated Return, and Original Loan Amount will be very helpful. Also the effects of verifiable income and home ownership should faciliate larger amounts

Univariate Exploration¶

Estimated Return¶

In [22]:
plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
bins = np.arange(0, loans.EstimatedReturn.max()+0.05, 0.01)
plt.hist(data = loans, x = 'EstimatedReturn', bins = bins);
plt.title('Distribution of Estimated Returns from loans')
plt.xlabel('Estimated Return on loans');

This shows the distribution to be multimodal. The highest peak between 0.05 and 0.10 (which is another peak) then there is a small peak around 0.15.

This indicates that Prosper projects to averagely make 5-15% return on loans.

In [34]:
# plot matrix: sample 5000 loans so that plots are clearer and render faster
loans_samp = loans.sample(5000)
g = sb.PairGrid(data = loans_samp.dropna(), vars = numeric_variables)
g = g.map_diag(plt.hist, bins=20)
g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter, alpha=0.2);

High positive correlation between BorrowerAPR and Estimated Return which means the higher the APR the higher the estimated return

The correlation coefficient of borrower APR and loan original amount is negative, which suggests that is the more the loan amount, the lower the APR.

Estimated Return is more negatively correlated with Prosper Rating than Prosper Score

As expected Prosper Ratings and Prosper Score are highly correlated Though it would seem that Prosper rating give a sharper and more definitive picture than Prosper Scores

BorrowerAPR has high negative correlation with Prosper Rating and a mild negative correlation with Prosper Score

plt.title('Borrower APR across rating and term')
plt.ylabel('Borrower APR')
ax.set_yticklabels([],minor = True);

The borrower APR generally decrease with the increase of borrow term for people with 1.0-4.0 ratings. But for people with 5.0-7.0 ratings, the APR actually increases with the borrow term

Loan amount, term and ratings suggest that Loan amount increases across the three terms with better ratings

Borrower APR decreases with better ratings while Loan amount increases with better ratings
